Sequential (cache-friendly)Random (cache-hostile) <pre><code>double sum = 0.0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; ++i) {
  sum += a[i];  // Each cache line covers a[i..i+7]; 8 loads per fetch.
}
</code></pre> <p>The hardware prefetcher detects the stride-1 pattern and begins loading the next cache line before the current one is exhausted. Effective bandwidth approaches the hardware peak (~50–200 GB/s on DDR5).</p> <pre><code>double sum = 0.0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; ++i) {
  sum += a[idx[i]];  // idx[i] is random; each load is a different cache line.
}
</code></pre> <p>Every access is likely a cache miss. The prefetcher cannot predict the pattern. Effective bandwidth collapses to the random-access rate (~5–20 GB/s), because 64 bytes are fetched to use 8.</p>
